title.narrative: Number of Companies that have actually received investor finance

comment.narrative: The first Matchmaking sessions took place mid October 2016. Accordingly no deals have been finalized yet up till this point as potential deals are still in the negotiations phase.

The earlier strategy of the Alliance was adjusted as reported in the annual reviews of 2016 and 2017. This decision was due to the challenge faced by the Alliance in engaging international investors with start-ups from the region due to their readiness to receive investments and the political & economic instability factors facing the region. The Alliance also realized that having the sessions alone would not be enough since the entrepreneurs are not necessarily ready to meet investors and more one on one mentoring and guidance was needed to prepare them for that. The strategy of the newly designed interventions was based on the following approaches: 1. Work with promising startups with high potential of job creation through mentoring and counselling on refining their business models to become both; (1) more investment ready and (2) provide with guidance on access to different other sources of finance. 2. Stimulating the local investment Climate through organizing networking events for local investors and sharing with them information about our promising startups and work on mitigating investment deals with both parties. As a result of this new approach between 2017 and 2018 the alliance successfully supported 8 start-ups to acquire equity based investments and 5 grants from donor agencies. As a result of the 13 facilitated financing opportunities the companies supported generated more than 132 fulltime employment opportunities and 1326 part-time opportunities.

title.narrative: Job Creation
Number of Jobs which the programme contributed to create

comment.narrative: Baseline Value still to be determined
Target is to be achieved by the end of the programme

The alliance relied on two strategies for job creation through the LEAD programme; (1) jobs to be created through Self employability and start-ups and MSMEs supported by the alliance and (2) through employability trainings and job placement and linking activities. The alliance initially believed that the job placement and training would yield the most results, however the entrepreneurial support activities proved to be more rewarding and resulted in overpassing the targeted number by more than 35%.

title.narrative: Coworking spaces serve as a support for entrepreneurs and in particular women to develop their businesses.
The percentage of women in the number of young people who are part of the coworking space community

description.narrative: This indicator will be measured on the basis of Community data from the participating coworking spaces

comment.narrative: Baseline value still to be determined
Target to be reached at the end of the period

Generally, for Egypt and Tunisia, the alliance measured a higher concentration of female entrepreneur in spaces part of the alliance than other spaces in the rest of the entrepreneurs ecosystem (the control group). In our assessment of this topic the alliance realized that around 41% of coworkers are female, in spaces part of supported by LEAD.

The spaces set up by the LEAD alliance are currently hosting more than 600 coworkers on daily basis. and more than 19000 young men and women have either attended events in the spaces or participated in trainings, workshops or other similar activities hosted by the spaces.

title.narrative: The percentage of women in the number of young people who make use of the coworking spaces’ services

description.narrative: This indicator will be measured on the basis of Community data from the participating coworking spaces.

comment.narrative: Baseline value still to be determined
Target to be reached at the end of the period

We believe the main reason for the relatively high number of women users (taking into effect the culture in the middle east and average participation rate of women in the workforce) comes from the fact that the program mainly works with spaces outside of the capital cities. Considering the cultural restrictions imposed on women, unlike men, women cannot travel to the capital cities to seek better employment opportunities, accordingly the spaces offered them an opportunity to connect with like minded individuals and a community of young men and women we seek to startup their businesses or work remotely.
